ologies, contrary to\nthe massive elliptical galaxy hosts of radio-powerful AGNs. The prevalence of\nlate-type hosts could suggest that triggering via secular, disk-based processes\nhas increased importance for HERGs with lower radio powers (e.g. disk\ninstabilities, large scale bars).\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 3 May 2019 18:00:06 GMT"}],"update_date":"2019-05-15"}
{"id":"1905.01316","submitter":"Leonardo Banchi","authors":"Leonardo Banchi, Jason Pereira, Seth Lloyd, Stefano Pirandola","title":"Convex optimization of programmable quantum computers","comments":"merged with arXiv:1905.01318","journal-ref":"npj Quantum Information volume 6, Article number: 42 (2020)","doi":"10.1038/s41534-020-0268-2","report-no":null,"categories":"quant-ph cond-mat.other math-ph math.MP physics.comp-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  A fundamental model of quantum computation is the programmable quantum gate\narray. This is a quantum processor that is fed by a program state that induces\na corresponding quantum operation on input states. While being programmable,\nany finite-dimensional design of this model is known to be nonuniversal,\nmeaning that the processor cannot perfectly simulate an arbitrary quantum\nchannel over the input. Characterizing how close the simulation is and finding\nthe optimal program state have been open questions for the past 20 years. Here,\nwe answer these questions by showing that the search for the optimal program\nstate is a convex optimization problem that can be solved via semidefinite\nprogramming and gradient-based methods commonly employed for machine learning.\nWe apply this general result to different types of processors, from a shallow\ndesign based on quantum teleportation, to deeper schemes relying on port-based\nteleportation and parametric quantum circuits.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 3 May 2019 18:00:06 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Tue, 19 May 2020 16:25:31 GMT"}],"update_date":"2020-05-20"}
